{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "In this paper, I raise an objection to Philip Go GLYPH<;11>; 's 'Revelation Thesis' as articulated in his Consciousness and Fundamental Reality (Go GLYPH<;11>; , 2017).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The upshot is that the Revelation Thesis is false.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Transparency in general is a feature of certain concepts; 'A transparent concept reveals what it is for its referent to exist' (Go GLYPH<;11>; , 2017, p.97).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Go GLYPH<;11>; notes that Chalmers' famous two-dimensional argument against physicalism presumes that there are no radically opaque concepts.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "By allowing that there might be radically opaque concepts, but restricting his claims of transparency to direct phenomenal concepts, Go GLYPH<;11>; crafts an argument against physicalism that is much more resistant to critique.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Indeed, as Go GLYPH<;11>; says, 'without phenomenal transparency, the epistemic gap between the physical and the experiential has no metaphysical significance' (Go GLYPH<;11>; , 2017, p.17).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Go GLYPH<;11>; 's Revelation Thesis entails what I will call the Identity of Indiscriminable Phenomenal Properties (IIPP).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "IIPP If, in forming direct phenomenal concepts, a concept user attends to separateaspectsofherexperience, andfindsthemtype-indiscriminable, then those aspects belong to the same phenomenal type.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "I maintain that the revelation thesis entails IIPP.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "A corollary of IIPP is that there are no type-indiscriminable di GLYPH<;11>; erences between direct phenomenal concepts.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Another closely related consequence of RT is that direct phenomenal concepts do not admit of borderline cases.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "I conclude, then, that IIPP is false.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Since IIPP is entailed by Go GLYPH<;11>; 's revelation thesis, we can infer by contraposition that it, too, is false.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
